ty histories. The book argues that the substances and their histories have shaped cultural consciousness, and that Romantic era texts formally encode this shaping. Matthew Rowney draws together processes, beings, and things, both from the Romantic period and from our current ecological moment, to re-invoke a lost heritage of cultural relations with common substances. Enabling a fresh reading of Romantic literature, In Common Things prompts a reevaluation of the simple, the everyday, and the common, in light of their contributions to our contemporary sense of ourselves and our societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCommerce in literature. 0aCulture in literature. 0aEcology in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh  aFelicia Hemans.  aJohn Clare.  aMary Prince.  aMary Wollstonecraft.  aRomantic literature.  aWilliam Wordsworth.  acommodity history.  acultural history.  aeco-criticism.  aenvironmental history.  agothic.  amoss.  aoil.  asalt.  astone.  awood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754347140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487543471423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487543471/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK